PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12274
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract This article contrasts two auction formats often used in public procurement: first price auctions with ex post screening of bid responsiveness and average bid auctions (ABAs), in which the bidder closest to the average bid wins. The equilibrium analysis reveals that their ranking is ambiguous in terms of revenues, but the ABA is typically less efficient. Using a data set of Italian public procurement auctions run alternately under the two formats, a structural model of bidding is estimated for the subsample of first price auctions and used to quantify the efficiency loss under counterfactual ABAs.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - RUMORS AND SOCIAL NETWORKS
AU  - Bloch, Francis
AU  - Demange, Gabrielle
AU  - Kranton, Rachel
